title: Issue with importing builtins in a VS Code Jupyter notebook
body:
## Describe the bug

Running into an issue with importing builtins in a VS Code Jupyter notebook.

Here's the error:

```python
from uptrain.framework.builtins import CheckResponseFacts

response_facts_check = CheckResponseFacts()
```

```sh
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
ImportError                               Traceback (most recent call last)
/Users/danielgwilson/local_git/patient-matching/python-notebooks/uptrain_sandbox.ipynb Cell 6 line 1
----> 1 from uptrain.framework.builtins import CheckResponseFacts
      3 response_facts_check = CheckResponseFacts()

File ~/local_git/patient-matching/.venv/lib/python3.11/site-packages/uptrain/framework/builtins.py:8
      6 from .checks import Check
      7 from uptrain.operators import Histogram
----> 8 from uptrain.operators import (
      9     ResponseFactualScore,
     10     ResponseCompleteness,
     11     ResponseRelevance,
     12     ContextRelevance,
     13     LanguageCritique,
     14     ToneCritique,
     15     ResponseCompletenessWrtContext,
     16     GuidelineAdherenceScore
     17 )
     19 # -----------------------------------------------------------
     20 # Context related
     21 # -----------------------------------------------------------
     23 CheckContextRelevance = lambda: Check(
     24     name="score_context_relevance",
     25     operators=[ContextRelevance()],
     26     plots=[Histogram(x="score_context_relevance")],
     27 )

ImportError: cannot import name 'GuidelineAdherenceScore' from 'uptrain.operators' (/Users/danielgwilson/local_git/patient-matching/.venv/lib/python3.11/site-packages/uptrain/operators/__init__.py)
```

Trying to follow the custom evals tutorial
https://docs.uptrain.ai/tutorials/customized-evaluations

## To Reproduce

title: Why set request timeout just for OpenAI?
body:
Hey @Dominastorm, 

Why set the request timeout for just openai? 
https://github.com/uptrain-ai/uptrain/blob/a663b2787a0bba54d4685b35a21e8774a7453288/uptrain/operators/language/llm.py#L54

title: Why not use ContextWindowExceedError instead?
body:
Hey @Dominastorm, 

LiteLLM exposes a custom exception for context window errors called ContextWindowExceededError. It's a subclass of Invalid Request Error, but this way it ensures that context window exceptions across all providers are mapped to the same error. 

https://github.com/uptrain-ai/uptrain/blob/a663b2787a0bba54d4685b35a21e8774a7453288/uptrain/operators/language/llm.py#L79


More on this here: https://docs.litellm.ai/docs/exception_mapping#custom-mapping-list

Feature Enhancement: Added Description to Chart Visualization

This pull request introduces a new feature that allows adding descriptions to chart visualizations, enhancing their context and understanding. Descriptions are now supported not only for the MultiPlot operator but also for individual chart types like LineChart, ScatterPlot, BarChart, Histogram, and CustomPlotlyChart. Additionally, this update includes comprehensive docstrings for the affected classes in the operator section, providing clear usage instructions.

Changes:
- Added description feature to chart visualizations
- Descriptions supported for MultiPlot and individual chart types
- Comprehensive docstrings added for certain classes in operators

Please review and merge.

title: Added description attribute to charts, also added documentation for certain classes
body:
## Description

This pull request introduces enhancements to the `uptrain` library's chart visualization operators to support descriptions for charts and subplots. The changes allow users to provide descriptions for individual charts and subplots, which are displayed underneath the corresponding graphs.

Some documentation for classes in operators has also been added.

### Changes Made

1. **Description Support for Individual Charts**: Added support for adding descriptions to individual charts (e.g., `LineChart`, `ScatterPlot`, etc.). The `run` method of each chart class has been modified to include an annotation below the graph if a description is provided.

2. **Description Support for Subplots**: Extended the `MultiPlot` operator to allow descriptions for each chart within the subplot. Descriptions are positioned below the graphs of each chart in the subplot.

3. ** Documentation or certain classes in operators has been added


### Example Usage

description = "" , can be added as an attribute when creating a plot
